{"/service/ndnp/iahi/batch_iahi_jackson_ver01/data/sn86061215/00415668764/1908051201/1035.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME 60\nkf\n.1. -Vl\\\n':|l\nMAN ESCAPES\n\u2022\"1\n-jt\n-Sis\nS\"-i\n'V ./i\ns? *W\nPi+\nBY A MARGIN\nBEORGE ANDERSON OF\n'a MO* SPENT NIGHT\nBUT ESCAPES\nTARKIO,\nAT FARM,\nMUR'DERESS\nGOES TO, TESTIFY.\nV-\nTOILS TIGHTENING\nAROUND LAMPHERE\nEVIDENCE SECURED THAT HEL\n6ELEIN HAD TUFT OF HAIR IN\nV.' -T CLINCHED HAND THAT CORRE-\n&SPONDS WITH SUSPECTS,\n|5yj St Joseph, Mo., May 11\u2014\"Be\ncause I had no money I now be\nlleye Is the only thing that saved\nme from being murdered by Mrs,\njj|5 Gunness near Laporte,\" said Geo.\nAnderson of Tarkio, Mo., last\nf| night, as he boarded the Rook\nIsland \"flyer\" for Chicago, where\nhe will offer his personal testi\n.gH|mony and letters written him by\n^'.\"Mrs. Gunness, to the authorities.\nAnderson, who is a Swede and 39\nyears old, belfeves the woman is\nii'\u00ab| still alive and that she set fire to\np\" the farmhouse herself.\nAnderson Had Narrow Escape.\ny$**\"s Two years ago while at Mon-\nvtv\nteith, Mich., he answered one of\nMrs. Gunness' advertisements\nposing himself as a wealthy far\ns\u00bb mer. She wrote him to come on.\nHe did so, but upon finding he\nhad no money she was incensed,\nbut told him to spend the night at\nsgher place. He went to bed but\nwas awakened and found the\nwoman bending over him. He\np? j. spoke to her and she ran out of\nf-^the room. Greatly frightened, he\ndid not close his eyes after that\n4\nand at daylight he left the place.\nik-i3''' -v\nLaporte, Ind., May 11. The au\nthorities of the county today are busy\nweaving together the shreds of evi\ndence relied upon to connect Ray\nLamphere with the deaths at the Gun\nness farm, and will have their case\nas complete as possible when the\ngrand jury meets next week. As yet\nthe defense has not revealed to any\ngreat extent what attitude it will as\nsume. Neither Lamphere nor his coun\nsel will discuss the matter with any\none further than to claim that Mrs.\nGunness is still alive and that she\nfired her own house that burned her\nchildren to death.\nWhile Prosecutor Smith denounces\nthis theory as absolutely improbable,\nyet this impression is becoming wide\nspread, despite the almost total ab\nsence of evidence to support it.\nThe weather again today was very\nthreatening. Some rain has fallen,\nthough not in- sufficient quantities to\ndelay the sheriff's operations at the\nGunness farm.\nHegelein Fought for Life.\nThat Andrew Hegelein did not give\nnp life without a struggle is evidenced\nby the fact that in one of his clinch\ned hands was a brown tuft of short\nhair, which is said to correspond\nclosely with the hair covering the\nhead of Ray Lamphere. This new\nphase of the mysteries disclosed in\nthe deposition of Dr. Myer, one of the\nan exhaustive examination of Hege\nexamining physicians who went into\nlein's body.\nMorbid Crowd at Farm Sunday.\nTwenty thousand people swarmed\ninto Laporte yesterday to make a Ro\nman holiday of \"murder farm.''\nThey came in trains, in automo\nbiles, buggies, wagons, and on bicy\ncles and hundreds walked from neigh\nboring towns to see the ruins of the\nhome and the private burying ground\nof this most fiendish murderess of\nthe age.\nThe scene at the Gunness \"grave\nyard\" farm was the strangest in mur\nder history annals. Never before has\nanything been enacted to equal it.\nMen and women were drawn from\nfar and near by the uncanny fascina\ntion of terrible crimes, and when\nthey approached the grewsome scene\nthey were met by hawkers selling\npopcorn, ^peanuts, lemonade and pos\ntal cards.\nOn the edge of a hole from which\ntwo of the bodies of the female Blue\nbeard had been dug, a man had erect\ned an ice cream booth and dispensed\npink ice cream and cake to the visit\nors.\nEvidence of Woman's Crimes.\nWilliam Brogiski, a Polandor, living\nwith a farmer neighbor of Mrs. Gun\nness, was called upon during the\nyears of 1906-07 to dig three holes in\nthe barn lot of the Gunness place. He\nwas told by Mrs. Gunness the holes\nwere to be utilized for rubbish and\nfarm refuse. Mrs. Gunness designat\ned the dimensions of the holes which\nBrogiski says were about six feet long\nand four feet wide In all of these\nholes bodies have been found.\nif\nMM\nAmerican Trooper\nKills And Wounds\n6 of His Comrades\nManila, May 11.\u2014A telegram\nreceived by the adjutant gen\neral announces that private\nMike Beacham of the first\nUnited States cavalry, ran\namuck, killing three and wound\ning three of his comrades. .The\ndead are:\nWILLIAM DOEY, first Ser\ngeant.\nG. WILSON, private.\nTHOMAS WOODWARD, pri\nvate.\nThe wounded are:\nEdward Woodward, private\nwas fatally wounded. It is\npresumed Beacham was insane\nwhen he committed the deed.\nOKLAHOMA HIT\nBY A TORNADO\nLOSS IS HEAVY\nMANY KILLED AND INJURED IN\nSTORM WHICH DESTROYED\nSEVERAL SMALL TOWNS.\u2014\nREPORT SHOW DAMAGE GREAT\nWoodward, Okla., May 11.\u2014A suc\ncession of tornadoes swept over a dis\ntrict lying 25 miles southwest, south\nand southeast of Woodward late yes\nterday and last night. Several small\nisolated towns off the railroad and\nwithout telegraphic communication\nare reported to be destroyed. Many\npeople were injured and several were\nkilled.\nThe Known Casualties.\nThe known casualties are:\nAt Arnett, one man killed and a half\ndozen persons injured, one fatally,\nAt Vici, Dr. Hauser, a physician,\nfatally injured.\nAt Matual\u2014Arthur Sibel, his wife\nand several others were seriously in\njured.\nGrand, the county seat of Bills\ncounty, is said to have been wholly\nwrecked.\nThe towns of Estelle, Cooley and\nRichmond are reported to have been\ndevastated. All these places are\ntwenty-five miles from a railroad.\nAt Little- Robe, 55 miles southwest\nof Woodward, Mrs. J. B. Hale was\nkilled.\nThe little town of Cestoi in Dewey\ncounty is reported to have been wiped\noff the map. No details are obtain\nable.\nA BIG YEAR FOR\nHOME COMPANIES\nSTATE INSURANCE ORGANIZA\nTIONS SHOW INCREASE WHILE\nOUTSIDERS LOSE.\nDes Moines, May 11.\u2014(Special)\u2014\nThe auditor's annual life insurance re\nport filed today shows an increase of\nover $3,000,000 of insurance in force\nat the close of last year. The Iowa\nold line companies gained over $2,000,\no-0 and the Iowa fraternals over $5,\n000,000. The outside companies lost\nheavily in the amount of business\ncarried, the old liners showing a de\ncrease of over $3,000,000.\nEGGS LIVE STOCK?\nIowa Importer Seeks to Evade Tariff\nby Novel Propo\nsition.\nMay 11.\u2014Is\negg\nWashington,\nlive stock?\nIf it is bought for the purpose of\nhatching, is it live stock for breeding\npurposes\nG. F. Statter of Sioux City, has the\ndepartment of the treasury worrying\nabout these and sundry collateral\nquestions. Mr. Statter sent to Eng\nland for a couple of dozen eergs of the\nBlack Orpington, an especially aristo\ncratic \"general purpose\" hen that is,\na hen that can lav an egg every day\nand at the same time be eaten for\ndinner with satisfaction and comfort.\nThe cheerful Joker who billed the\neggs out of England and who didn't\nknow anything about the tariff valued\nthem at $100. When they got to the\ncustom-house at Sioux City duties of\n$25 \"were assessed against them. Mr.\nStatter protested. He had heard of\nthe famous ruling of Secretary Shaw\nthat frogs are poultry for the pur\nposes of tariff, and he figured that\neggs were live stook, potentially, at\nleast.\nUnder the law registered live stock\nImported for breeding purposes is en\ntitled to come in free. But the de\npartment decided against the Sioux\nCity man, and his only hope is to re\nopen the case. Meanwhile he is for\ntariff revision\u2014not at the hands ot\nits friends.\nRace Track Gambling Forbidden.\nWashington, D. C., May 11. The\nhouse today accepted the senate\namendments to the bill prohibiting\nrace track gambling in the District of\nColumbia and thus finally passed it.\ntu.\n3\n^\u2022Si\nBE EVENTFUL\nGATHERING OF NOTABLE MEN OF\nNATION DEVOTED TO DEVIS\nING PLANS FOR CONSERVING\nRESOURCES OF COUNTRY\nDAWSON WANTS THE\nPROCEEDINGS READ\nIOWA CONGRESSMAN INTRO\nDUCES RESOLUTION IN\nFOR PRINTING 100,000\nHOUSE\nCOPIES\nOF ALL DELIBERATIONS\nWashington Bureau of\nThe Ottumwa Courier\nWashington, D. C., May 11.\nRepresentative Pawson of Iowa to\nday Introduced a resolution in the\nHouse providing for the printing of\n100,000 copies of the proceedings of\nthe coming conference over the con\nservation of National Resources. Mr.\nDawson holds the conference is of so\nmuch importance that its proceedings\nshould be widely circulated.\nJ. C. Welllver.\nWashington, D. C., May 11.\u2014It is\nperhaps safe to say that no gathering\nof public men ever held in the United\nStates is attracting so much general\nattention as the conference for the\nnatural resources to be held this week\nat the White House. As an evidence\nof the wide spread interest that is be\ning taken in this conference, it may\nbe said that the committee having in\ncharge the arrangements has been,\nwithin the last two weeks, absolutely\nswamped with requests for admission\ncards, and such requests, to the num\nber of several thousand, have been\nrefused.\nThe sessions of the conference \"are\nto be held in the oast room of the\nWhite\" House and the limited space\ntogether with the large number of\nspecially invited delegates, has made\nit necessary to cut down the allot\nment of tickets in every possible way.\nWhen it is remembered that at this\nconference practically the entire gov\nernment of the United States will be\ngathered together in a single room\nthe necessity for extraordinary pre\ncautions will be recognized. Consid\nering the fact that the governors of\npractically all the states and .territor\nies, the congress of the United States,\nthe United States supreme court, the\npresident's cabinet and the president\nhimself, will be in attendance, it will\nbe seen that the part of wisdom dic\ntates the adoption of every possible\nsafe-guard.\nFrom the correspondence received\nin Washington in relation to this con\nference it is beginning to be felt more\nand more that out of the conference\nwill grow a great, broad national or\nganization of state executives look\ning toward a nation-wide plan of con\nservation, perpetuation and utilization\nof natural resources.\nThe program for the conference ?s\ngiven herewith for the first time:\nMay 13.\n10:00 a. m.\u2014Conservation as a Na\ntional Duty, Theodore Roosevelt,\npresident of the United' States.\n2:30 p. m.\u2014Mineral Resources:\nOres and Related Minerals, An\ndrew Carnegie.\nMineral Fuels, Dr. I. C. White,\nprofessor of geology, University\nof West Virginia, and state geol\nogist of West Virginia.\nGeneral discussion, opened by\nJohn Mitchell, former president\nof the United Mine Workers of\nAmerica.\nMay 14.\n10:00 a. m.\u2014Land Resources:\nSoli, Professor T. C. Chamber\nlain, University of Chicago, for\nmerly state geologist of Wiscon\nsin, president University of Wis\nconsin, and geologist U. S. geo\nlogical survey.\nForests, R. A. Long, president of\nthe Long-Bell Lumber Co., Kan\nsas City, Mo.\nPublic Health, Dr. George M.\nKober, dean of the medical de\npartment, Georgetown Univer\nsity, Washington, D. C., formerly\npresident of the Medical society\nof the District of Columbia.\n2:30\u2014Land Resources:\nReclamation by Irrigation and\nDrainage, Dr. George C. Pardee,\nformer governor of California.\nGrazing and Ctock-raislng, Hon.\nJ. A. Jastro, president of the\nAmerican National Livestock as\nsociation.\nThe Public Lands and Land Ten\nure, Judge Joseph M. Carey, for\nmerly United States senator from\nWyoming.\nMay 15.\n10:00 a. m.\u2014Water Resources:\nTransportation, James J. Hill,\npresident of the Great Northern\nRailway.\nNavigation, Professor Emory R.\nJohnson, professor of Transpor\ntation and Commerce, Univer\nsity of Pennsylvania formerly\nIsthmian (janal Commissioner.\nWater Power, H. S. Putnam.\nAmerican Institute of Electrical\nEngineers.\n2:30 p. m.\u2014General Discussion.\nfe\nS?\n\u2022fc\nOTTUMWA, WAPELLO COUNTY, IOWA, TUESDAY MAY 12, 1908\n1 I\nA DESCRIPTION\nOF THE EDIFICE\nNEARLY $1,000,000 WILL BE SPENT\nIN CONSTRUCTION\u2014CARNE\nGIE GAVE $750,000.\nThe imposing international building\nwill stand on an attractive site cover\ning about five acres to the south of\nand in close proximity to the White\nHouse, the State, War and Navy De\npartment building, the Corcoran Art\nGallery, and that of the Daughters of\nthe American Revolution. It is also\nnear the Washington Monument. The\ndimensions of the building will be\nappro^tndately 100 by 160 feet, Its main\nportion staiding two \u2022stories above a\nhigh studded basement and being in\nturn surmounted by dignified bal\nlustrades. The rear portion in order\nto cover a capacious assembly hall\nwill rise still higher. The genera!\narchitecture will suggest Latin-Ameri\ncan treatment out of respect to the\nfact that 20 of the 21 republics are of\nLatin origin, at the same time pos\nsession such monumental character\nistic as will make it harmonize with\nthe general scheme for the improve\nment of Washington. It will be con\nstructed throughout of steel and con\ncrete, with the effect of a Spanish\nstucco finish and with white marble\nsteps, foundations and trimmings. A\nlarge reading room will be a feature\nwhere can be seen all the South as\nwell as North American publications,\nbesides Important historical data.\nStructure to be Unique.\nA beautiful assembly chamber that,\nfor present purposes, may be called\nthe \"Hall of the American Ambassa\ndors,\" will provide the only room of\nits kind in the United States especial\nly designed for international con\nventions, receptions to distinguished\nforeigners, and for diplomatic and\nsocial events of a kindred nature. The\nbureau Is rictly an international and\nivatntfxinnH\nby tlie joint contributions, based on\npopulation, oi um zj American gov\nernments.\nNearly $1,000,000 will be spent in\nconstruction and fitting up the build\ning of which Andrew Carnegie contri\nbuted $750,000. It will be unique, not\nonly for Washington, but in all the\nworld, serving as an International\nheadquarters of offices in one National\ncapital of 21 American nations, the\nnearest approach to it being the new\nTemple of Peace, now veing erected\nat the Hague.\nWants Stewart Charges Investigated.\nWashington, D. C., May 11. \u2014Sena\ntor Rayner today introduced a resolu\ntion authorizing the President to con\nvene a court of inquiry to investigate\nthe charges against Colonel William\nF. Stewart, who has been detailed to\nsevere until retirement at the aban\ndoned military post at Fort Grant,\nArizona.\nANOTHER PIONEER CALLED.\nL. Giiiiland, a Prominent Pioneer Citi\nzen, Dies at His Home in\nIconium Thursday.\nTyrone.\u2014L. Giiiiland, one of the\nold and highly respected Franklin\ntownship farmers died at his home\nin Iconium Thursday from what is\nsupposed to be an acute attack if\nheart disease. The deceased came to\nthis community from Pennsylvania in\n1S63 and located on a farm about\nthree miles souta of this place where\nhe resided up until about two years\nago, when he surrendered the active\nmanagement of the farm to his son\nRoy, and with his wife removed to\nIconium, a little town just south of the\nnorth line of Appanoose county,\nwhere he resided at the time of his\ndemise. The funeral was held Friday\nfrom the family residence to the cem\netery in that town. He leaves sur\nviving him three daugaters, Mrs. jas.\nTurner, Mrs. Fred Sheldon and Mrr.\nThompson, and one son Roy Giiiiland,\nwho resides on the home place.\n1\n4i\nMmmstrnikm\nNotables Who Took Part in Laying Corner\nStone of Imposing International Building\nBureau of American Republics as it, will appear when completed. At\nextreme right is shown John Barrett, director, Theodore Roosevelt, .Elihu\nRoot at top of group. Mr. 'Joaquin NabiBco, Brazilian ambassador at lower\nleft. Cardinal Gibbons at lqwer right, Andrew \"Carnegie in center.\nAND\nTHE PRESIDENT\nCOMMITTEE FROM OPTIMISTIC\nST .LOUIS ORGANIZATION\nSEES EXECUTIVE.\nWashington, D. C., May 11.\u2014A com\nmittee from the National Prosperity\nassociation of St. Louis called on\nPresident Roosevelt today to urge his\naid in furthering their plans for en\ncouraging the return of prosperity\nthroughout the country. The commit\ntee found the president cordial in his\ntreatment and frank iti his expres\nsions of willingness to aid them in ev\nery way possible. A short speech was\nmade by E. C. Simmons, chairman of\nthe executive committee of the asso\nciation, which was responded to by\nthe president. Simmons urged that a\nhalt be called upon \"radical, hasty and\nexperimental legislation designed to\nregulate industry.\" He applauded the\npresident for the many reforms he\nhas instituted and brought about.\nYOUNG LIFE CL0SE8.\nMiss Florence Foley, a Well Known\nWayne Township Woman\nDied This Morning.\nTyrone, May 11.\u2014Miss Florence\nFoley, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Jas.\nFoley of Wayne township, died at the\nhome of her parents four miles north\nof Melrose at an early hour this morn\ning. The young lady had been ill\nfor several months and dissolution\nwas not wholly unexpected it comes\nas a shock to her large circle of\nfriends, who will mourn for a young\nlife as soon terminated.\nCLEVELAND 18 GOING HOME\nFormer President's Condition Im\nproves and He will Leave Lake\nwook for Princton This Week.\nLakewood, N. J., May 11.\u2014Reports\nfrom the Lakewood hotel last night\nwere that former President Cleveland\nhad passed a comfortable twenty-four\nhours and that his condition continues\nto Improve. He will return to his\nhome in Princton thiB week.\nThe windows of the Cleveland apart\nments are full of flowers, 'which have\nbeen sent to the patient by friends.\nMrs. Cleveland left the patient twice\nyesterday, In the morning to attend\nservices in the Presbyterian church,\nwhere in past years she has been a\nregular attendant, and In the after\nnoon for an hour's walk about town.\nIn reply to inquiries by friends in\nthe church congregation she stated\nthat Mr. Cleveland was doing nicely\nand had passed a comportable night.\nCamp Creek, 8. D., Destroyed by Fire\nDeadwood, S. D., May 11. \u2014Camp\nCreek, a town of 40 population on the\nLittle Missouri river north of here,\nwas destroyed by fire two days ago.\nThe loss is $200,000. The news cot\nhere by courier.\n.4\n'IQfv'\nMr\nibjiiiuo JiBis\n^0|OOS iuai.ui'isiii onus I*\nBISHOP MIILDOON\nOUT IN DENIAL\nREPORT OF CLERGYMAN'S ELEC\nTION TO HEAD DIOCESE\nCAME FROM CHICAGO.\nChicago, May 11.\u2014Bishop Peter\nMuldoon, auxiliary bishop and vicar\ngeneral of the Chicago archdiocese,\nvigorously denied yesterday a rumor\nthat he had been .appointed bishop of\nthe newly created Rockford diocese.\nHe saM the report had originated in\nChicago and that no action could be\nexpected from Rome for some time.\nHis assertions were confirmed by\nthe papal delegate to the United\nStates, the MoBt Rev, Diomede Fal\nconio, who announced In Washington\nthat no appointment to the Rockford\nbishopric had been made by the pope.\nThe names of Chancellor E.\nDunne and Father E. A. Kelly were\nsent to Rome along with Bishop Mul\ndoon's, and they were recommended\nas worthy candidates for the office.\nChancellor Dunne, expressed the opin\nion that if the rumor were unfounded\nit would still prove a correct proph\necy.\n\"Bishop Muldoon's appointment to\nthe Rockford diocese is almost an ab\nsolute certainty,\" he said. \"All of us\nwho are interested personally in the\nappointment will be delighted to see\nthe bishop get it, for he is eminently\nfitted for the position.\"\nSEES GOOD TIIVtES\nGeorge Gould Says Financial Tide\nHas Turned\u2014 Confidence Has\nBeen Restored.\nNew York, May 11.\u2014George J. Gould\nsay that he believes the corner has\nbeen turned in the financial situation\nand that, while he looked for some\nwhat unfavorable railroad earnings^\nperhaps until July, he was inclined to\ntake an optimistic view of the out\nlook. He said that while all roads\nwould not be able to borrow with the\nsame facility as in the Pennsylvania,\nhe was of the opinion that the success\nof the Pennsylvania and of the Inter\nborough Rapid Transit Issues had\nmade It measureably easy for other\nroads to place loans.\nMr. Gould said he attached a great\ndeal of Importance to the change that\nhas taken place in the attitude of the\npolitical leaders of Texas toward the\nrailroads of that state. Mr. Gould said\nthe change in the sentlmont of the\npeople In Texas with respect to the\nrailroads had also become pronounced\nwithin' the last three weeks. He be\nlieves that this more friendly senti\nment on the part of the politicans and\nthe people will gradually become gen\neral throughout the United StateB. He\nattributes the improvement in the out\nlook to the supreme court decision in\nthe rate cases.\nReferring to the Western Union Tel\negraph company, Mr. Gould said that\nthe company had one million dollars\ncash in the bank, was paying all its\nexpenses promptly and that operating\nexpenses had been so much reduced\nthat net earnings, despite a falling off\ngross receipts, have not recently\nin\n1\nshown any material loss.\ny--\n4#'\nmm\nTARY ROOT COMPLIMENT,\ntvr\nREPRESENTATIVES FROM ALL\nAMERICAN REPUBLICS TAKB IM\nPART IN ELABORATE CER&\nMONIES AT WASHINGTON\nPRESIDENT GIVES\nCARNEGIE PRAISEl\nREFERS TO WORK DONE BY PHtl\nANTHROPIST IN CAUSE OP\nPEACE ALSO GIVES SECRE-\n4?\n~x\nTSTUMBEB 111\nni\nWashington, D. C., May 11.\u2014Prest\ndent Roosevelt will at three o'clock\nthis afternoon lay the corner stone of'\nthe first lnternatlnonal temple of\npeace, friendship and commerce yet,'''\nto be erected, a tangible evidence ot\nthe desire of twenty-one American Re\npublics that war shall be no more la\nthe Western World and that material\nprosperity, promoted by international\ntrade shall take its place.\nFitting the historical Importance ofMrf\nthe event the exercises are to be\nmade Impressive by the participation \"Ml\nof heads of each of these republics.\naddresses by President\nFollowing\nRoosevelt, Secretary Root, AmbaBS*-\nBuilding Owned by all Republic*.\nThe new building is to be the joint, Ml\nproperty of all republics. The site pro-%^\nvided by the American congress con-^/jJ\nsistB of the historic old Vanness homes!?/\nand is within a few hundred yards\nthe White House, and adjacent to the^\nState, War and Navy buildings.\nEminent Speakers Heard.\nDirector John Barrett, of the Trav1\nreau in a very brief talk in which h\u00ab\nreferred to the great assistance given 'M\nby Secretary Root toward the accom-H\nplishment of the work and hla effort\",^#?\nin behalf of the advance of the\nreau work Introduced the seoretarjr\nof state, who is chairman of the gov\nerning board of the bureau as the prov? 4\u00a7fi\nsiding officer. Cardinal Gibbons da\nllvered the invocation, which was\nfollowed In turn by an address by vJ\nMr. Root, the reading of congratula\ntory messages from American presl\ndents and addresses by President\nRoosevelt, Ambasador Nabuco and\nAndrew Carnegie. Ceremonies Incl\ndent to the laying of the corner stone S|f\nclosed the exercises. Inscribed om\nthe corner stone are the following\nwords:\n\"Building of the American republics.*\nErected through the public spirited\ngift of Andrew Carnegie and the con\ntrlbutions of all the republics opon r'^3\nland provided by the government olK\nthe United States. May 11, 1808.\" '*Jj|\nPresident Thanks Carnegie.\nPresident Roosevelt In his address\nsaid:\n\"This is a menorable occasion for\nall the peoples of the Western Heml- 14?\nsphere. The building, the corner\nstone of which we lay today, em- of\nphaslzes by its existence the growing ''M\nsense of solidarity of interest and\naspiration among all the peoples at the\nNew World. It marks our recognition\n-I\nVwd 'r\ndor Nabuco, of Brazil and Andrew\nCarnegie, a cabled sentiment,\npressing the hearty approval of eachi A if\npresident, will be read. Cardinal j5$S|\nbons and Bishop Cranston will\nnounce the invocation and benediction\non the work done and the United(v^''f\u00ae\nStates marine band will render aeleo^lV\ntlons of pan-American music, especial-? ''\u20221\nly prepared for the occasion.\nThree quarters of a million. aolUmiffi.\ntowards the construction of the bulld\"^'\\v\nlng was the contribution of Carnegie,^\nwhile each republic has added an ap\"!\u00bb\nproprlation to the fund. Invitations tof'}'\nthe exercises have been accepted\nthe entire diplomatic corps In Wash-^n^La\nlngton as well as by high officials\nall branches of the American govern^\"\nment.\nof the need to knit ever closer to\ngether all the republics of the Western\nHemisphere through the kindly bonds\nof mutual justice, good will, and sym- \u00ab\\t?\npathetic comprehension.\n\"At the outset, on behalf of all oC\nus I wish to thank Mr. Carnegie for his\ngenerous gift\u2014a gift to all the nations\nof the New World, and therefore pre\neminently fitting as coming from one\nwho has so sincerely striven for the\ncause of peace among nations for\nwhile we have yet a long, path to\ntread before we can speak with any\ncertainty of the day when wars shall g|g\ncease from the earth, we of this West- $t,\nera Hemisphere, by movements such\nas that symbolized by this building,\nhave taken great strides toward Be\ncuring permanent peace among our\nselves.\nPraise for 8ister Republics. \\\\j\\\n\"In the next place, as president of\nthis Republic I greet the represent\u00ae\ntives of all our sister Republics to\nthe south of us.. In a sense, you are\nour elder sisters and we the younger '^v\npeople, for you represent a. more an\ncient civilization on this continent\nthan we do. Your fathers, the Spanish\n(Continued on page two), -J\"\nk,f?]\n1\nI\ne. i'\nV\"\n\u2022\u2022\u2022\"iftilitT nUitffll","height":"26228","width":"21263"}}
